data.content:
Here's the mapping:

| NUnit | xUnit equivalent |
|---|---|
| `[SetUp]` | Constructor |
| `[TearDown]` | `IDisposable.Dispose` |
| `[OneTimeSetUp]` / `[OneTimeTearDown]` | `IClassFixture<T>` + fixture's `Dispose` |

The converted code:

```csharp
// Fixture for one-time setup/teardown
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        Database.Initialize();
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();
    }
}

// Test class
public class CustomerRepositoryTests : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    // Runs before each test (replaces [SetUp])
    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture fixture)
    {
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    // Runs after each test (replaces [TearDown])
    public void Dispose()
    {
        _context.Dispose();
    }

    [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

Key changes:
- **`IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>`** — xUnit creates one `DatabaseFixture` instance shared across all tests, replacing `[OneTimeSetUp]`/`[OneTimeTearDown]`
- **Constructor** replaces `[SetUp]` — xUnit creates a new class instance per test
- **`IDisposable.Dispose`** replaces `[TearDown]`
- If you need the fixture instance (e.g., a shared DB connection), use the `fixture` constructor parameter
